=====================================================
std::function (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=====================================================

Header:
#include <functional>

-----------------------------------------------------
1. What is std::function?
-----------------------------------------------------

std::function is a polymorphic function wrapper introduced in C++11.

It can store and invoke ANY callable object:

1. Normal functions
2. Lambdas
3. Functors (objects with operator())
4. Member functions
5. Bind expressions

Syntax:

std::function<ReturnType(ParameterTypes)> name;

Example:

std::function<int(int,int)> f;

means:

Return type : int
Parameters  : (int,int)

-----------------------------------------------------
2. Why do we need std::function?
-----------------------------------------------------

Lambdas have anonymous compiler-generated types.

Example:

auto add = [](int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
};

Type of add:

main::{lambda(int,int)#1}

This type cannot be written explicitly.

Sometimes we need:

1. Store different callables in same variable
2. Pass lambdas as function arguments
3. Return lambdas from functions
4. Store callbacks

std::function solves this problem.

-----------------------------------------------------
3. Syntax
-----------------------------------------------------

std::function<return_type(parameter_types)> name;

Example:

std::function<int(int,int)> func;

-----------------------------------------------------
4. Store a Lambda
-----------------------------------------------------

std::function<int(int,int)> add =
[](int a, int b)
{
    return a + b;
};

cout << add(10,20);

Output:

30

-----------------------------------------------------
5. Store a Normal Function
-----------------------------------------------------

int sum(int a, int b)
{
    return a+b;
}

std::function<int(int,int)> f = sum;

cout << f(10,20);

Output:

30

-----------------------------------------------------
6. Store a Functor
-----------------------------------------------------

class Add
{
public:
    int operator()(int a, int b)
    {
        return a+b;
    }
};

std::function<int(int,int)> f = Add();

cout << f(10,20);

Output:

30

-----------------------------------------------------
7. Store Capturing Lambda
-----------------------------------------------------

int x = 10;

std::function<int(int)> f =
[x](int a)
{
    return a + x;
};

cout << f(5);

Output:

15

-----------------------------------------------------
8. Passing Lambda to Function
-----------------------------------------------------

void execute(std::function<void()> func)
{
    func();
}

int main()
{
    execute([]()
    {
        cout<<"Hello";
    });
}

Output:

Hello

-----------------------------------------------------
9. Returning Lambda from Function
-----------------------------------------------------

std::function<int(int)> getAdder()
{
    return [](int x)
    {
        return x + 10;
    };
}

int main()
{
    auto f = getAdder();

    cout << f(5);
}

Output:

15

-----------------------------------------------------
10. Callback Example (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------------------

void process(std::function<void(int)> callback)
{
    callback(100);
}

int main()
{
    process([](int x)
    {
        cout << x;
    });
}

Output:

100

Callbacks in GUI/Event systems often use std::function.

-----------------------------------------------------
11. Why not use auto?
-----------------------------------------------------

auto add =
[](int a,int b)
{
    return a+b;
};

Pros:
✓ Zero overhead
✓ Fastest
✓ Compiler knows exact type

Cons:
✗ Cannot write type explicitly
✗ Hard to return/store generically

-----------------------------------------------------
12. Why not use Function Pointer?
-----------------------------------------------------

Function pointer:

int (*fp)(int,int);

Can store:

✓ Normal functions
✓ Non-capturing lambdas

Cannot store:

✗ Capturing lambdas
✗ Functors

Example:

int x = 10;

auto l =
[x](int a)
{
    return a+x;
};

int (*fp)(int) = l;

Compilation Error.

-----------------------------------------------------
13. std::function can store Capturing Lambdas
-----------------------------------------------------

int x = 10;

std::function<int(int)> f =
[x](int a)
{
    return a+x;
};

Works perfectly.

-----------------------------------------------------
14. Performance Cost
-----------------------------------------------------

auto lambda
-------------
No type erasure
Usually inline
Fastest

Function Pointer
----------------
Small overhead

std::function
-------------
Type erasure
Possible heap allocation
Indirect call
Slower than auto

Hence:

Prefer:

auto

Use std::function only when polymorphic callable storage is needed.

-----------------------------------------------------
15. Type Erasure (Interview Favorite)
-----------------------------------------------------

std::function hides the actual callable type.

These all become:

std::function<int(int,int)>

int sum(int,int);
lambda;
functor;

Actual types are erased.

Only signature remains:

int(int,int)

This is called Type Erasure.

-----------------------------------------------------
16. Most Asked Interview Questions
-----------------------------------------------------

Q1. What is std::function?
A:
A polymorphic wrapper capable of storing any callable object.

Q2. Why is std::function needed?
A:
Because lambdas have anonymous types and sometimes we need generic callable storage.

Q3. Can std::function store capturing lambdas?
A:
Yes.

Q4. Can function pointers store capturing lambdas?
A:
No.

Q5. Does std::function use type erasure?
A:
Yes.

Q6. Is std::function slower than auto lambda?
A:
Yes, due to type erasure and indirect invocation.

Q7. When should I use std::function?
A:
Callbacks, event handlers, APIs, returning lambdas, generic callable storage.

-----------------------------------------------------
17. Interview One-Liner
-----------------------------------------------------

auto
----
Exact lambda type
Fastest
No overhead

Function Pointer
----------------
Only functions and non-capturing lambdas

std::function
-------------
Can store ANY callable object
Uses type erasure
Some runtime overhead
Best for callbacks and generic callable interfaces.
